        '<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"><span>1. How to help a friend/relative who is struggling with addiction? </span></p>\n<p dir="ltr"><a href="https://sukoonhealth.com/rehabilitation-services/drug-deaddiction/"><span>Addiction</span></a><span> is a complex illness with multiple aspects and it requires a combination of pharmacological and psychological group therapy interventions. As a family or a friend, you can help them understand that it\'s an illness and not who they are. We can do the same by not labeling their condition and motivating them to seek </span><a href="https://sukoonhealth.com/get-in-touch/"><span>help</span></a><span>. </span></p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"> </p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"><span>2. What are the signs and symptoms to recognise that someone has an addiction problem?</span></p>\n<p dir="ltr"><span>Individuals may typically develop a strong desire to take the </span><a href="https://sukoonhealth.com/rehabilitation-services/alcohol-deaddiction/"><span>substance</span></a><span>, difficulties in controlling its use, persisting in its use despite harmful consequences, a higher priority given to substance use than to other activities and obligations, increased tolerance, and sometimes a physical withdrawal state.</span></p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"> </p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"><span>3. What is the difference between use and abuse?</span></p>\n<p dir="ltr"><span>Individuals consuming substances on an irregular basis, increasing the frequency and quantity of intake with the course of time can be considered as Substance-Use. However, when the individual is unable to control the urge, and it also starts impacting personal, occupational and social life, it can be considered as abuse. </span></p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"> </p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"><span>4. Can addiction be treated?</span></p>\n<p dir="ltr"><span>Yes, addiction can be managed and the treatment is tailor made as per individuals need and symptoms. Early identification and treatment are of vital importance. There are a range of effective treatments available. For any type of treatment, it is imperative that the person affected is proactive and fully engaged in their </span><a href="https://sukoonhealth.com/rehabilitation-centre-in-delhi/"><span>recovery</span></a><span> process. Many people with addiction who are diagnosed and treated respond well, although some might experience a relapse. Even in such cases, with careful monitoring and management, it is still quite possible to live a fulfilled and productive life. </span></p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"> </p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"><span>5. What are the risk factors involved in addiction?</span></p>\n<p dir="ltr"><span>Risk factors associated with addiction include family history of substance abuse, developmental history, using substances from an early age, personality traits, adverse life experiences, peer pressure, ability to cope from stressful situations and other mental health conditions. </span></p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"> </p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"><span>6. Can addiction lead to other mental health disorders? </span></p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"><span>Individuals with addiction and substance use may experience a range of co-occurring mental disorders and vice versa. These can include problems in impulse control, anxiety disorders, depression, attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), bipolar disorder, personality disorders, and schizophrenia. Treatment for both mental health problems and substance use disorders may include </span><a href="https://sukoonhealth.com/rehabilitation-centre-in-delhi/"><span>rehabilitation</span></a><span>, medications, support groups, and psychotherapy. </span></p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"> </p>\n<p dir="ltr" role="presentation"><span>7. How do you treat patients with addiction using psychotherapy?</span></p>\n<p dir="ltr"><span>In psychotherapy for addiction, multiple factors are focused upon including motivation, harm reduction, cognition, relationships and managing disruptive behavior. Each approach has its own helpful aspects and can assist people who are in recovery from addiction. Some examples of psychotherapy include </span><a href="https://sukoonhealth.com/mental-health-consultation/psychoanalytic-therapist-for-mental-health/"><span>psychoanalysis</span></a><span>, creative </span><a href="https://sukoonhealth.com/mental-health-consultation/art-therapy-for-mental-health/"><span>arts</span></a><span> therapy, supportive psychotherapy, psychodynamic therapy, behavioral therapy, cognitive behavioral therapy, dialectical behavior, contingency management, and more.</span></p>',
